            "description": "",
            "details": "<p data-start=\"182\" data-end=\"369\"><em>Cebelü’s-S̠elc, Cebelü’l-Lübnān, Cebel-i Ukām</em>: These are three mountains contiguous with one another which, extending from south to north, appear as a single mountain range. The southern one, which lies near Ṣafed (modern Safed<em data-start=\"423\" data-end=\"438\">, </em>Israel), is <em>Cebel-i S̠elc</em>. It stretches northward and passes beyond the city of <em>Dımaşḳ</em> (modern Damascus, Syria). The people of that region call it <em>Cebel-i Süneyd</em> [appears as <em>Sebḳad</em> in one of the manuscripts of this work]. After this extension, the mountain that faces the west of <em>Ba‘albek</em> (modern Baalbek, Lebanon) is called <em>Cebel-i Lübnān</em> (Mount Lebanon). Just as it passes beyond <em>Ba‘albek</em> and reaches the mountain lying to the east of <em>Ṭrablūs-Şām</em> (modern Tripoli, Lebanon), that mountain is called <em>Cebel-i ‘Akkār</em>—for <em>‘Akkār</em> is the name of a fortress located on its summit, and by association it has given the mountain its fame.</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"159\" data-end=\"548\">After it continues northward and passes beyond <em>Ṭrablūs</em> (modern Tripoli, Lebanon), they give the name <em>Cebel-i Ukām</em> to the mountain that first reaches <em>Ḥıṣnu’l-Ekrād</em>, then <em>Ḥimṣ</em> (modern Homs, Syria), then <em>Ḥamā</em> (modern Hama, Syria), <em>Shīrez</em> (likely <em data-start=\"470\" data-end=\"486\">Shayzar?, Syria</em>), and the borders of <em>Efāmiyye</em> (modern <em data-start=\"529\" data-end=\"544\">Apamea, Syria</em>). Then, passing beyond that and continuing in extension, the mountain appearing opposite <em>Cebel-i Ukām</em> is called <em>Cebel-i Şaḥşebū</em>, meaning that it is named in attribution to the village of <em>Şaḥşebū</em>. This mentioned mountain passes by <em>Ma‘arra</em>, <em>Sermīn</em> (modern Sermīn, Syria), and the western side of <em>Ba‘albek</em>, and becomes connected to <em>Cebel-i Rūm</em>. Likewise, <em>Cebel-i Ukām</em>, extending northward, passes <em>Mehveb</em>, then through <em>S̠uġūr</em>, <em>Bekkās</em>, and <em>Ḳayṣer</em>, and reaches <em>Anṭākiyye</em> (modern <em data-start=\"1115\" data-end=\"1132\">Antakya, Turkey</em>), where it terminates. Opposite this, there is yet another mountain, and the <em>Nehr-i ‘Āṣī</em> (the Orontes River) flows between the two of them. [translation]</p>",
            "end": 1599,
